    mechanism:
      "**AHK-Cu** is a copper-chelating tripeptide composed of alanine, histidine, and lysine bound to a single copper(II) ion — structurally distinct from the better-known GHK-Cu (glycine-histidine-lysine copper) but mechanistically related. Both are copper tripeptides; both deliver bioavailable copper to target tissues; both engage related signaling pathways. The structural difference (alanine vs glycine at position 1) produces tissue-targeting differences — AHK-Cu has been studied predominantly in hair follicle contexts while GHK-Cu has broader skin / regenerative applications. **Mechanism — copper delivery to follicular tissue**: copper is an essential cofactor for multiple enzymes involved in connective tissue and keratin synthesis: lysyl oxidase (collagen and elastin cross-linking), tyrosinase (melanin synthesis), Cu/Zn superoxide dismutase (antioxidant defense), cytochrome c oxidase (mitochondrial energy production). Hair follicles are metabolically active tissue with high copper requirements during the anagen (growth) phase. Copper tripeptides deliver copper to tissue more efficiently than free copper salts, partly via the chelated form's ability to penetrate epidermis and partly via the peptide carrier's tissue-targeting properties. **Mechanism — anagen phase support and follicular cycling**: hair follicles cycle through three phases: anagen (active growth, 2-7 years), catagen (regression, 2-3 weeks), and telogen (resting, 2-4 months). In MPB, the anagen phase shortens progressively with each cycle, leading to follicle miniaturization. AHK-Cu supports anagen-phase metabolism via copper delivery, with literature describing extension of anagen phase duration and increased follicle proliferation in animal and in-vitro models. The clinical evidence base is modest — AHK-Cu has not had the rigorous human RCT testing that Finasteride and Minoxidil have received — but mechanism is sound and topical use is well-tolerated. **Mechanism — combined protocol context (the practical reality)**: AHK-Cu is rarely used as monotherapy. Standard hair-loss protocols layer AHK-Cu with Finasteride (DHT reduction) and Minoxidil (vasodilation / potassium channel opening), with AHK-Cu providing the copper-mediated follicular metabolic support component. Some scalp formulations combine AHK-Cu with GHK-Cu for broader copper tripeptide coverage. Pre-formulated cosmetic scalp products typically include AHK-Cu at low concentrations (0.5-2% peptide content) alongside other actives. **Mechanism — distinction from GHK-Cu**: GHK-Cu is the more thoroughly studied copper tripeptide with applications spanning skin barrier function, wound healing, and broader regenerative signaling beyond hair. AHK-Cu has a narrower documented application focus on hair follicle metabolic support. The two are complementary rather than competitive — combined use in scalp formulations is common. See the GHK-Cu tile for broader copper tripeptide context. **Mechanism — pharmacokinetics (topical)**: short topical residence on scalp; absorption via follicular ostia and epidermal pathways; systemic absorption limited but not zero; no measurable systemic copper accumulation at standard cosmetic concentrations. **Pharmaceutical status**: AHK-Cu is not a pharmaceutical; no FDA approval; cosmetic-tier ingredient marketed as a hair-care peptide; widely available in scalp serums, shampoos, and combination hair-loss formulations.",
